QD/TiO
                        2
                     @PI/PES

ce:section.ce:para:
This study employed different membranes with varying contents of QD/TiO2, pure TiO2 membrane, and commercial TiO2 membrane (named as P25) to conduct photocatalyst tests of methylene blue (MB), while 0.1 g TiO2, QD/TiO2, and P25 were dissolved in MB solution for 1 h under stirring to approach adsorption balance statue, and then recorded the adsorption value once per 2 h under UV light emission (Fig. 4
                        ). The synthesized TiO2 membrane could degrade 14.7% of MB without the addition of QD; the degradation of MB increased from 14.7% to 45.5% after 5.0% addition of QD. However, when QD concentration was increased to 7.0%, the degradation of MB reduced to 20.4%. This reduction can be attributed to higher photo intensity generated by 7.0% QD/TiO2 compared to that by 3.0% and 5% QD/TiO2 as observed in photoluminescence analysis; higher concentration of QD/TiO2 (7.0%) is also accompanied with recombination of electron and hole reaction (Fig. 5
                        ). As the loading of carbon QDs increased, the peak of the photoluminescence (PL) spectrum tended to decrease; however, when the loading of carbon QDs increased to 7.0%, the intensity of PL spectrum increased. On comparing different concentrations of QD/TiO2, addition of QD/TiO2 at high concentrations would form a layer of continued-thin membrane to cover the surface of metal oxide carrier, hindering photo collection, electric charge transition, and reducing photocatalyst efficiency. Ke et al., subjected QD/TiO2 synthesized by l-ascorbic acid and tetrabutyl titanate to 10 ppm MB degradation test, at 2.5%, 5.0%, and 7.5% QD/TiO2 concentrations. Moreover, the degradation efficiency of MB was as high as 90% for QD/TiO2, which was 3.6 times higher than that of pure TiO2 [36], so QD addition indeed improved the photocatalyst efficiency. According to results of Ke et al., this study synthesized different ratio of QD/TiO2 on PI/PES membrane to conduct MB degradation tests.
